{
  "questions": [
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "A child scrapes their knee on the playground. The skin is broken and dirt gets into the wound, but after washing and bandaging it, the knee heals without infection within a week.",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Memory cells are part of the second line of defense and require previous exposure to the same specific pathogen. The quick healing without infection suggests faster-acting defenses were at work.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Memory cells recognized the dirt bacteria from a previous infection"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! The first line of defense includes cells that immediately attack any foreign material entering through broken skin. These rapid responders can handle many threats before specialized defenses are needed.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Patrolling cells destroyed foreign material before it could multiply"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Antibodies are highly specific to particular invaders and must be created in response to each new threat. They're not pre-made for every possible pathogen a person might encounter.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Antibodies were already present in the bloodstream to neutralize all bacteria"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "While bandages help, dirt had already entered the wound. The healing without infection indicates internal defense mechanisms dealt with invaders that got through the broken skin barrier.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The bandage physically blocked all bacteria from entering the wound"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What defense likely prevented infection?"
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "Two siblings catch the same flu virus. One sibling had the flu two years ago; the other never has. The sibling who had it before feels better in 3 days, while the other is sick for a week.",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Physical barriers like skin and mucus don't improve based on previous infections. They're the same for everyone regardless of infection history.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Their physical barriers were stronger from previous exposure"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Exactly! After the first infection, some specialized cells remain that 'remember' that specific virus. When it appears again, these cells enable a much faster response, shortening the illness.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Cells from the previous infection recognized and attacked the virus immediately"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "First-response cells work the same way regardless of past infections. The faster recovery comes from a different type of cell that provides long-term protection against specific threats.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The first sibling's patrolling cells were permanently more active"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "While some antibodies may persist, the key factor is specialized cells that can rapidly produce new antibodies when they detect a familiar threat, rather than antibodies continuously circulating for years.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Antibodies from two years ago were still circulating in the bloodstream"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Why did one sibling recover faster?"
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "A person develops a bacterial throat infection. Doctors detect that specialized proteins in their blood are binding to the bacteria, making it easier for defense cells to destroy them.",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "These proteins don't destroy invaders themselves. Instead, they act as markers that help other parts of the immune system identify and eliminate the threat more effectively.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "They directly kill bacteria by dissolving their cell walls"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! These targeting proteins attach to specific invaders like a label, making them easy for destructive cells to identify. This precision allows the immune system to focus on actual threats without damaging healthy tissue.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "They tag specific invaders so they can be found and destroyed"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Physical barriers work independently of these proteins. Once bacteria are already inside the body, different mechanisms are needed to deal with them.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "They strengthen physical barriers to prevent more bacteria from entering"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Actually, these proteins are part of the specialized, slower response system. The immediate response involves different cells that attack first, before these specific proteins are created.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "They immediately respond before specialized defenses can activate"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What is the role of these proteins?"
    },
    {
      "format": "sortOrder",
      "feedback": "This sequence reflects how the immune system escalates its response. Physical barriers are the first line, but when breached, immediate-response cells act quickly. If the threat persists, the slower but more precise targeting system activates. Finally, the system creates lasting protection by storing information about the invader for future encounters.",
      "items": [
        "Virus particles bypass the broken skin barrier",
        "General defense cells patrol the area and begin consuming foreign material",
        "Specialized cells identify the specific virus and create matching proteins",
        "Long-lasting cells form that will recognize this virus in future infections"
      ],
      "question": "Arrange these events in the order they would typically occur when a new virus enters the body through a cut"
    },
    {
      "format": "matchColumns",
      "pairs": [
        {
          "left": "A person gets chickenpox once as a child and never gets it again despite exposure",
          "right": "Cells retain information about previous invaders"
        },
        {
          "left": "Nasal mucus traps dust and germs before they reach the lungs",
          "right": "Physical barriers block entry of threats"
        },
        {
          "left": "A blood test shows proteins that only bind to strep bacteria, not other bacteria",
          "right": "Targeting proteins are specific to particular invaders"
        },
        {
          "left": "A small splinter causes redness and swelling as the body reacts to foreign material",
          "right": "Immediate responders attack anything recognized as foreign"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Match each real-world observation with the immune system principle it demonstrates"
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "A scientist is developing a treatment for a new disease. She wants to help patients fight the infection more quickly the first time they encounter it, not just during repeat infections.",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Excellent thinking! Transferring cells that already 'know' the disease would give patients the advantage of a remembered threat even on first exposure. This is essentially how vaccines work—creating memory without the actual illness.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Introduce memory cells from recovered patients"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "While barrier enhancement might prevent some infections, it doesn't help once someone is already infected. The question asks about fighting an existing infection more quickly.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Strengthen patients' skin and mucus membranes"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "More general responders might help slightly, but they lack the speed and precision advantage that comes from cells that have specific information about the threat.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Increase the number of general patrol cells in the bloodstream"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Antibodies are highly specific—each type only works against one particular invader. Creating antibodies that bind to many different diseases would likely make them less effective or cause them to attack the body itself.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Inject antibodies that bind to many different diseases at once"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Which approach would help with first-time infections?"
    },
    {
      "format": "fillBlank",
      "answers": [
        "first",
        "destroying",
        "proteins",
        "memory cells"
      ],
      "distractors": [
        "second",
        "identifying",
        "barriers",
        "antibodies",
        "patrolling",
        "B cells"
      ],
      "feedback": "This sequence captures the escalating immune response: immediate action from the first defense system, destruction of threats by rapid responders, creation of specific targeting proteins when needed, and formation of long-term memory cells that provide lasting protection.",
      "question": "Complete this description of how the immune system responds to a bacterial infection",
      "template": "When bacteria enter through a wound, the [BLANK] line of defense activates instantly. Roaming cells begin [BLANK] the foreign material. If the infection persists, specialized cells produce [BLANK] that attach to the bacteria. After recovery, [BLANK] remain in the body to enable faster responses to the same bacteria in the future."
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "A person with a genetic condition lacks the cells that create targeting proteins. They can still fight some infections, but certain types of bacteria and viruses overwhelm their defenses.",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "The fact that they can fight some infections shows they have more than just physical barriers. They must have other internal defense mechanisms still functioning.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Their physical barriers work normally but they lack all internal defenses"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Exactly right! Their first line of defense—both barriers and rapid-response cells—functions normally, handling simpler threats. But without the specialized targeting system, they can't efficiently fight infections that require precise identification and marking.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "They have immediate-response defenses but lack the precise targeting system"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The condition specifically prevents them from making targeting proteins. The issue is with the current infection response, not with forming future immunity.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "They can make targeting proteins but cannot form lasting protection"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Memory cells are formed by the same system that creates targeting proteins. If that system doesn't work, neither the immediate specialized response nor the memory function would be available.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Their memory cells work but cannot respond quickly to repeat infections"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Why can they fight some infections but not others?"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "questions": [
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "A programmer writes a function that adds two variables called 'total' and 'count' using the '+' operator. What has the compiler identified after the first stage of processing?",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! Lexical analysis breaks the code into tokens - the smallest meaningful units like identifiers, operators, and keywords. Each element becomes a separate token that later stages can work with.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "The variables, operator, and keywords are separated into distinct meaningful units"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Not yet. Checking type compatibility happens in semantic analysis, which comes later. The first stage just identifies the individual pieces without evaluating their meaning.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The compiler checks whether 'total' and 'count' are compatible for addition"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "That's close, but this describes parsing, which is the second stage. The first stage simply breaks the code into individual tokens before any structural relationships are established.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "A tree structure is created showing how the addition operation relates to the variables"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Code generation happens at the very end, after all the analysis stages. The compiler must understand and validate the code before it can generate machine instructions.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The operation is translated directly into processor instructions"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What happens during this initial stage?"
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "A developer writes: if (x > 5 { print(x) }. The code won't compile even though all the words are valid programming keywords and the logic makes sense.",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Exactly! The parser builds a tree structure showing how elements relate to each other. When it can't find the closing parenthesis needed to complete the if-statement structure, it reports a syntax error.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "The parsing stage, which builds structural relationships and detects the missing closing parenthesis"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Lexical analysis only identifies whether individual pieces are valid tokens. All the keywords, operators, and symbols here (including the single parenthesis) are valid tokens - the problem is how they're arranged.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The lexical analysis stage, which identifies invalid tokens"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Semantic analysis checks meaning and type compatibility, not structure. By the time code reaches this stage, all parentheses must already be properly matched.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The semantic analysis stage, which checks logical consistency"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The compiler never reaches code generation with structural errors. Invalid syntax is caught much earlier, preventing later stages from attempting to process malformed code.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The code generation stage, when attempting to create machine instructions"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Which stage catches this problem?"
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "A program tries to assign the text \"hello\" to a variable that was declared to hold only integers. The syntax is perfect and all parentheses match correctly.",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! Semantic analysis checks whether code is meaningful, including type compatibility. It ensures that values match the types expected by variables and operations, even when the syntax is structurally perfect.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "During semantic analysis, which verifies that operations make logical sense"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The parser only verifies that code follows structural rules like matching parentheses. Type mismatches are logically invalid but structurally valid, so they pass through parsing.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "During parsing, which checks the structural arrangement"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Lexical analysis just identifies tokens - both \"hello\" and integer variables are valid tokens. It doesn't understand what types mean or whether they're compatible.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "During lexical analysis, which identifies valid programming elements"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The compiler catches type errors before attempting code generation. Trying to generate machine code for logically invalid operations would be inefficient and could miss important errors.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "During code generation, when the incompatibility becomes impossible to translate"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Where does the compiler catch this error?"
    },
    {
      "format": "sortOrder",
      "feedback": "This sequence reflects the compiler's multi-stage pipeline: first breaking code into tokens (lexical analysis), then understanding structure (parsing), then validating meaning (semantic analysis), and finally producing executable output (code generation). Each stage builds on the previous one's work.",
      "items": [
        "Identifying individual elements like variable names, numbers, and the division operator",
        "Building a tree showing the division operation applies to the sum of two numbers",
        "Verifying that all variables contain numeric types compatible with arithmetic",
        "Producing processor instructions that perform the calculation"
      ],
      "question": "A programmer submits code that calculates the average of two numbers. Arrange the stages in the order the compiler processes this code:"
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "A software engineer notices their compiler takes several seconds to process a large file. They wonder why it can't just immediately convert the code to machine instructions in one quick step.",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Exactly! Breaking compilation into stages follows the principle of separation of concerns. Each stage focuses on one aspect - identifying tokens, building structure, checking meaning, or generating code - making the complex task of translation more manageable and reliable.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Each stage handles a specific type of transformation, making complex translation manageable by solving one problem at a time"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The stages aren't about speed control. They exist because jumping directly from source code to machine instructions is too complex. Each stage simplifies the overall problem by handling one transformation.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Multiple stages slow down compilation to prevent processor overheating"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Stages run sequentially, not in parallel, because each stage needs the previous stage's output. The pipeline structure exists for logical organization, not parallel processing.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Different stages run on different processors to speed up compilation"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "While most compilers use similar stages, the reason is practical, not regulatory. This architecture emerged because it effectively solves the problem of translating high-level code to machine instructions.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Programming language standards require exactly these stages in this order"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Why does compilation use multiple stages?"
    },
    {
      "format": "matchColumns",
      "pairs": [
        {
          "left": "\"Unexpected symbol '@' in source code\"",
          "right": "Lexical analysis - the symbol isn't a valid token"
        },
        {
          "left": "\"Expected ';' after statement\"",
          "right": "Parsing - the structural rules aren't followed"
        },
        {
          "left": "\"Cannot multiply boolean by integer\"",
          "right": "Semantic analysis - the operation doesn't make logical sense"
        },
        {
          "left": "\"Function result stored in register EAX\"",
          "right": "Code generation - translating to machine-level details"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Match each error message to the compilation stage that would detect it:"
    },
    {
      "format": "fillBlank",
      "answers": [
        "lexical analysis",
        "parsing",
        "semantic analysis",
        "code generation"
      ],
      "distractors": [
        "optimization",
        "linking",
        "interpretation",
        "debugging",
        "execution",
        "preprocessing"
      ],
      "feedback": "This sequence captures the compiler pipeline: lexical analysis breaks code into tokens, parsing creates structural relationships, semantic analysis validates meaning and types, and code generation produces executable instructions. Each stage depends on the successful completion of the previous one.",
      "question": "Complete the description of how a compiler processes the statement: result = calculate(x, y) + 10",
      "template": "The compiler first performs [BLANK] to break the statement into individual pieces like variable names, function calls, and operators. Next, [BLANK] builds a hierarchical structure showing that addition combines a function call with a number. Then [BLANK] verifies that the function returns a type compatible with addition. Finally, [BLANK] produces the actual processor instructions."
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "Two students are debugging their code. One gets an error about an \"unrecognized character\" while the other's error says \"type mismatch in assignment.\" Both errors prevent compilation.",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! Unrecognized characters are caught during lexical analysis, the first stage. Type mismatches are caught during semantic analysis, which only runs after lexical analysis and parsing both succeed. The second student's code is structurally valid but semantically flawed.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "The first student's error happens earlier in processing; the second student's code passed more stages before failing"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "These errors come from different stages. Character recognition happens in lexical analysis, while type checking happens in semantic analysis. The stage that catches an error tells you how far the code made it through the pipeline.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Both errors occur at the same stage, just with different messages"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Actually, the opposite is true. The first error occurs in an earlier stage (lexical analysis), meaning the compiler couldn't even begin to understand the code's structure. The second error made it further through the pipeline.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The first error is less serious because it occurs in a later stage"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Error difficulty isn't determined by which stage catches it. However, the stage does indicate what kind of problem exists: the first has invalid characters while the second has type incompatibility.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The second student's error will be easier to fix because it involves types"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What does this tell us about their code?"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "questions": [
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
